x mkdir
x touch
no-touch
no-mkdir
link-ignore
git-ignore
ignore-needs
version
version-name
dependencies use IDs and reference the CACHE_DB for new ones
autodependency (bring in both)
uninit (remove from git history)
setup (put in setup mode and do the following)
	required
	set-cache-dir

test suite for everything (this MUST work pretty much all the time)

Usage: ./cache
	[ -  ]
Database stuff:
x	-e, --exists <arg>           Does this file exist? 
x	-c, --create <arg>           Add a package. 
x	-r, --remove <arg>           Remove a package. 
	-u, --update <arg>           Update a package. 
x		--mkdir <arg>             Make additional directories. 
x		--touch <arg>             Create additional files.
x		--no-mkdir <arg>          Skip directory creation.
x		--no-touch <arg>          Skip file creation.
x	-m, --commit <arg>           Commit changes to a package.
x	-n, --needs <arg>            Set a dependence. 
x	-x, --no-longer-needs <arg>  Unset a dependency. 
x		--list-needs <arg>        Set a dependence. 
		--list-versions <arg>     List all the versions out.
x	-k, --link-to <arg>          Put a package somewhere.
x		--symlink-to <arg>        Put a package somewhere.
x		--link-ignore <arg>       Ignore these when linking out.
x		--git-ignore <arg>        Ignore these when committing.
		--uninit <arg>            Remove all tracking information from git.
	-u, --uuid <arg>             Select by UUID. 
x	-b, --blob

	Parameter tuning:
		--version <arg>          Select or choose version. 
x	-s, --summary <arg>          Select or choose summary. 
		--produced-on <arg>      Select a date.
	-a, --authors <arg>          Select or choose a set of authors. 
	-q, --extra <arg>            Supply key value pairs of whatever else 
										should be tracked in a package. 

	General:
x		--set-cache-dir <arg>    Set the cache directory to <arg>
		--required <arg>         Define parameters required when creating a package.
		--cd <arg>               Use <arg> as the current cache directory.
										(Will fail if .CACHE_DB is not there.)
x	-i, --info <pkg>             Display all information about a package.
x		--contents <pkg>         Display all contents of a package.
x	-l, --list                   List all packages.
x	-d, --directory              Where is an application's home directory? 
x		--dist-info              Display information about how `cache` is setup
x		--install <arg>          Install this to a certain location. 
x		--uninstall              Uninstall this. 
x	-v, --verbose                Be verbose in output.
x	-h, --help                   Show this help and quit.

